---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Editorial Team | SexualHarassmentCalc';
const description = 'Editorial standards and contributor biographies for SexualHarassmentCalc, including Editor-in-Chief Devin Bertram and contributing writer Harlow Pace.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Editorial Team</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Devin Bertram (DB), Editor-in-Chief &mdash; EEOC Practice. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>
    Every page on SexualHarassmentCalc is written or reviewed by a practitioner with hands-on experience in employment-discrimination
    intake, EEOC procedure, or state fair-employment-agency practice. We do not publish anonymous content. The reviewer line on
    each page identifies the person responsible for accuracy as of the date shown.
  </p>

  <h2>Devin Bertram (DB) &mdash; Editor-in-Chief, EEOC Practice &amp; Title VII Lead</h2>
  <p>
    Devin Bertram has spent the last decade inside the intake and investigation pipeline that determines whether a workplace
    sexual-harassment complaint becomes a viable Title VII claim. After completing a paralegal certificate program with an
    employment-law concentration, Devin moved through three plaintiff-side employment-litigation boutiques before settling into
    a senior paralegal and HR-compliance lead role at a mid-market firm representing both employees and small employers.
  </p>
  <p>
    Devin holds the Society for Human Resource Management Senior Certified Professional (SHRM-SCP) credential, which requires
    annual recertification on Title VII enforcement, EEOC procedural updates, and state fair-employment developments. Day to day,
    Devin drafts EEOC charges and position statements, supervises evidence preservation in active matters, and runs the firm&rsquo;s
    internal training on the Speak Out Act of 2022 and post-#MeToo NDA/non-disparagement reforms in state legislation.
  </p>
  <p>
    On SexualHarassmentCalc, Devin owns the calculator math, the methodology page, the case-types deep dive, and the editorial
    standards. Pages reviewed by Devin carry the &ldquo;Reviewed by Devin Bertram (DB)&rdquo; line and a dated update.
  </p>

  <h2>Harlow Pace (HP) &mdash; State Harassment Statutes &amp; Procedural Reference</h2>
  <p>
    Harlow Pace is a paralegal with eight years of employment-litigation experience, the last four focused on multi-state matters
    where the interaction between Title VII and state fair-employment statutes determines case value. Harlow&rsquo;s desk reference
    on the FEHA, NYHRL, NJLAD, Illinois Human Rights Act, and Massachusetts Chapter 151B is the backbone of the state-law overlay
    you see in the calculator and the guides.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before moving full-time to employment work, Harlow spent three years in general civil litigation at a regional firm, which
    is where the procedural rigor comes from: the FAQ and the post-incident guide are largely her work. Harlow holds an ABA-approved
    paralegal certificate and is a member of the National Federation of Paralegal Associations (NFPA).
  </p>
  <p>
    On SexualHarassmentCalc, Harlow contributes the post-harassment guidance, the misconceptions guide, and the procedural detail
    inside the FAQ. Pages with substantial Harlow content carry a contributor line below Devin&rsquo;s reviewer credit.
  </p>

  <h2>Editorial standards</h2>
  <p>
    The site follows five rules. They are not aspirational &mdash; they are the rules a page must satisfy before it is published.
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Cite real authority.</strong> Statutes by U.S.C. section, cases by name and reporter cite, EEOC guidance by document name. No paraphrased legal &ldquo;rules&rdquo; without a source.</li>
    <li><strong>No legal advice.</strong> Every page is informational. The calculator outputs an educational range, not a case value. We do not represent any reader and no attorney-client relationship is formed by reading or contacting the site.</li>
    <li><strong>Plain language, not jargon.</strong> If a term requires explanation (<em>quid pro quo</em>, <em>Faragher</em>/<em>Ellerth</em>, constructive discharge), we define it the first time it appears on each page.</li>
    <li><strong>Dated reviews.</strong> Each page shows the reviewer and the month/year of last review. We revisit dated pages when material law changes (Speak Out Act, EEOC strategic plan updates, major Supreme Court decisions).</li>
    <li><strong>Direct the reader out.</strong> Every guide ends with a clear pointer: EEOC field-office locator, state agency, or an instruction to consult a plaintiff-side employment attorney before any deadline passes.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Corrections policy</h2>
  <p>
    If you spot a factual error, an out-of-date statute or case cite, or a worked example that no longer reflects current law,
    email <a href="mailto:hey@theclicklab.agency">hey@theclicklab.agency</a> with the page URL and the correction. We update
    promptly and add a dated note at the bottom of the affected page when the correction is substantive.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
